{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RPYkRnWgQGiM7jSiag1zmj","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→stepsCompleted: [1, 2, 3, 4]\n     3→inputDocuments:\n     4→  - architecture-v3.md\n     5→  - tech-spec-retro-pipeline-harness-fixes.md\n     6→  - tech-spec-rust-stack-support.md\n     7→  - tech-spec-multi-stack-support.md\n     8→---\n     9→\n    10→# Architecture v3 — Epic Breakdown\n    11→\n    12→## Overview\n    13→\n    14→6 migration phases from architecture-v3.md, mapped to epics 10-15. Each epic ships working software. No backward compatibility — breaking changes are acceptable. State migration handles upgrades automatically.\n    15→\n    16→## Epic List\n    17→\n    18→- **Epic 10: Stack Provider Pattern** — Eliminate 41 if/else branches. One file per language.\n    19→- **Epic 11: Unified State** — Consolidate 5 state files into 2. Schema versioning.\n    20→- **Epic 12: lib/ Restructuring** — Split oversized files. Domain subdirectories. Thin commands.\n    21→- **Epic 13: Agent Abstraction** — Ralph behind an interface. 28 files decoupled.\n    22→- **Epic 14: Process & Infra Fixes** — Retro pipeline, tech debt gate, Docker pre-check, observability choice, verify provisioning.\n    23→- **Epic 15: Enforcement** — CI file size gate, ESLint rules, boundary tests, template migration.\n    24→\n    25→---\n    26→\n    27→## Epic 10: Stack Provider Pattern\n    28→\n    29→Eliminate all stack conditionals outside `src/lib/stacks/`. Adding a language = adding one file.\n    30→\n    31→### Story 10-1: Create StackProvider interface and registry\n    32→\n    33→As a developer,\n    34→I want a StackProvider interface that encapsulates all language-specific behavior,\n    35→So that adding a new language requires only one new file.\n    36→\n    37→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n    38→\n    39→**Given** `src/lib/stacks/types.ts` exists\n    40→**When** inspected\n    41→**Then** it defines `StackProvider` interface with: `name`, `markers`, `displayName`, `detectAppType()`, `getCoverageTool()`, `detectCoverageConfig()`, `getOtlpPackages()`, `installOtlp()`, `getDockerfileTemplate()`, `getDockerBuildStage()`, `getRuntimeCopyDirectives()`, `getBuildCommands()`, `getTestCommands()`, `getSemgrepLanguages()`, `parseTestOutput()`, `parseCoverageReport()`, `getProjectName()`\n    42→\n    43→**Given** `src/lib/stacks/registry.ts` exists\n    44→**When** `detectStacks()` is called\n    45→**Then** it uses the registry's marker list (not hardcoded checks) to detect stacks\n    46→\n    47→**Given** the registry\n    48→**When** `getStackProvider('nodejs')` is called\n    49→**Then** it returns the NodejsProvider instance\n    50→\n    51→### Story 10-2: Implement NodejsProvider\n    52→\n    53→As a developer,\n    54→I want all Node.js-specific logic in one file,\n    55→So that Node.js behavior is encapsulated and testable in isolation.\n    56→\n    57→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n    58→\n    59→**Given** `src/lib/stacks/nodejs.ts` exists\n    60→**When** inspected\n    61→**Then** it implements all `StackProvider` methods for Node.js: package.json detection, vitest/jest/c8 coverage, npm OTLP packages, Dockerfile template, AGENTS.md commands\n    62→\n    63→**Given** the NodejsProvider\n    64→**When** `detectCoverageConfig()` is called on a project with vitest\n    65→**Then** it returns the same result as the current `detectNodeCoverageTool()`\n    66→\n    67→**Given** all Node.js if/else branches are removed from `coverage.ts`, `otlp.ts`, `docs-scaffold.ts`, `dockerfile-template.ts`\n    68→**When** `npm test` runs\n    69→**Then** all tests pass (0 regressions)\n    70→\n    71→### Story 10-3: Implement PythonProvider\n    72→\n    73→As a developer,\n    74→I want all Python-specific logic in one file,\n    75→So that Python behavior is encapsulated and testable in isolation.\n    76→\n    77→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n    78→\n    79→**Given** `src/lib/stacks/python.ts` exists\n    80→**When** inspected\n    81→**Then** it implements all `StackProvider` methods for Python: requirements.txt/pyproject.toml/setup.py detection, coverage.py, pip/pipx OTLP packages, Dockerfile template\n    82→\n    83→**Given** all Python if/else branches are removed from consumer files\n    84→**When** `npm test` runs\n    85→**Then** all tests pass\n    86→\n    87→### Story 10-4: Implement RustProvider\n    88→\n    89→As a developer,\n    90→I want all Rust-specific logic in one file,\n    91→So that Rust behavior is encapsulated and testable in isolation.\n    92→\n    93→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n    94→\n    95→**Given** `src/lib/stacks/rust.ts` exists\n    96→**When** inspected\n    97→**Then** it implements all `StackProvider` methods for Rust: Cargo.toml detection, app type (CLI/server/library/agent), cargo-tarpaulin, cargo add OTLP, multi-stage Dockerfile, `[dependencies.foo]` subsection parsing, `'library'` AppType\n    98→\n    99→**Given** all Rust if/else branches are removed from consumer files\n   100→**When** `npm test` runs\n   101→**Then** all tests pass\n   102→\n   103→### Story 10-5: Migrate all consumers to use StackProvider\n   104→\n   105→As a developer,\n   106→I want zero `if (stack === 'nodejs')` patterns outside `src/lib/stacks/`,\n   107→So that the stack abstraction doesn't leak.\n   108→\n   109→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   110→\n   111→**Given** `coverage.ts`, `otlp.ts`, `docs-scaffold.ts`, `dockerfile-template.ts`, `verify/env.ts`, `readme.ts`\n   112→**When** inspected\n   113→**Then** zero stack string comparisons remain — all use `provider.method()`\n   114→\n   115→**Given** a boundary test exists\n   116→**When** it scans `src/` for `stack === 'nodejs'` or `stack === 'python'` or `stack === 'rust'` outside `src/lib/stacks/`\n   117→**Then** it finds zero matches\n   118→\n   119→---\n   120→\n   121→## Epic 11: Unified State\n   122→\n   123→Consolidate 5 state files into 2. Schema versioning. Derived views.\n   124→\n   125→### Story 11-1: Unified SprintState schema with versioning\n   126→\n   127→As a developer,\n   128→I want one `sprint-state.json` with a versioned schema that contains all sprint runtime data,\n   129→So that state is never out of sync.\n   130→\n   131→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   132→\n   133→**Given** `sprint-state.json` has `version: 2` schema\n   134→**When** inspected\n   135→**Then** it contains: `stories`, `retries`, `flagged`, `epics`, `session`, `observability`, `run`\n   136→\n   137→**Given** an old `sprint-state.json` without `version` field\n   138→**When** `readSprintState()` is called\n   139→**Then** it auto-migrates to version 2 schema\n   140→\n   141→**Given** `.story_retries` and `.flagged_stories` files exist\n   142→**When** migration runs\n   143→**Then** their data is merged into `sprint-state.json` and the files are deleted\n   144→\n   145→### Story 11-2: sprint-status.yaml becomes derived view\n   146→\n   147→As a developer,\n   148→I want `sprint-status.yaml` generated from `sprint-state.json`,\n   149→So that there's one source of truth with a human-readable view.\n   150→\n   151→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   152→\n   153→**Given** `sprint-state.json` has story statuses\n   154→**When** `generateSprintStatusYaml()` is called\n   155→**Then** it writes a valid YAML file matching the current sprint-status.yaml format\n   156→\n   157→**Given** a story status changes in `sprint-state.json`\n   158→**When** `writeSprintState()` completes\n   159→**Then** `sprint-status.yaml` is regenerated automatically\n   160→\n   161→**Given** harness-run reads story statuses\n   162→**When** it queries state\n   163→**Then** it reads from `sprint-state.json` directly (not sprint-status.yaml)\n   164→\n   165→### Story 11-3: State reconciliation on session start\n   166→\n   167→As a developer,\n   168→I want state consistency verified at the start of every session,\n   169→So that desyncs from crashes or manual edits are caught immediately.\n   170→\n   171→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   172→\n   173→**Given** `sprint-state.json` and `sprint-status.yaml` are out of sync\n   174→**When** harness-run Step 1 pre-flight runs `reconcileState()`\n   175→**Then** `sprint-state.json` is authoritative and `sprint-status.yaml` is regenerated\n   176→\n   177→---\n   178→\n   179→## Epic 12: lib/ Restructuring\n   180→\n   181→Split oversized files into domain subdirectories. Move business logic from commands to modules.\n   182→\n   183→### Story 12-1: Split coverage.ts into domain subdirectory\n   184→\n   185→As a developer,\n   186→I want coverage logic in `src/lib/coverage/` with files under 300 lines each,\n   187→So that coverage code is maintainable and testable.\n   188→\n   189→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   190→\n   191→**Given** `src/lib/coverage/` exists\n   192→**When** inspected\n   193→**Then** it contains: `index.ts` (<50 lines, re-exports), `types.ts`, `runner.ts`, `evaluator.ts`, `parser.ts`\n   194→\n   195→**Given** each file in `src/lib/coverage/`\n   196→**When** line count is checked\n   197→**Then** no file exceeds 300 lines\n   198→\n   199→**Given** `parseTestCounts()` in `parser.ts`\n   200→**When** cargo workspace output is mixed with pytest-like output\n   201→**Then** cargo aggregation fires first (ordering guard test exists)\n   202→\n   203→### Story 12-2: Split docker.ts, otlp.ts, beads-sync.ts, doc-health.ts\n   204→\n   205→As a developer,\n   206→I want all 832/590/422/378-line files split into domain subdirectories,\n   207→So that the entire codebase respects the 300-line limit.\n   208→\n   209→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   210→\n   211→**Given** `src/lib/docker/` with `compose.ts`, `health.ts`, `cleanup.ts`\n   212→**And** `src/lib/observability/` with `instrument.ts`, `config.ts`, `backends.ts`\n   213→**And** `src/lib/sync/` with `beads.ts`, `sprint-yaml.ts`, `story-files.ts`\n   214→**When** each file is checked\n   215→**Then** no file exceeds 300 lines\n   216→\n   217→**Given** all splits complete\n   218→**When** `npm test` runs\n   219→**Then** all tests pass with 0 regressions\n   220→\n   221→### Story 12-3: Move business logic from status.ts command to status module\n   222→\n   223→As a developer,\n   224→I want `src/commands/status.ts` under 100 lines with logic in `src/modules/status/`,\n   225→So that status logic is testable without command wiring.\n   226→\n   227→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   228→\n   229→**Given** `src/modules/status/` with `index.ts`, `formatters.ts`, `endpoints.ts`, `drill-down.ts`\n   230→**When** `src/commands/status.ts` is inspected\n   231→**Then** it's under 100 lines — just arg parsing, module call, output formatting\n   232→\n   233→**Given** `src/modules/status/endpoints.ts`\n   234→**When** `buildScopedEndpoints()` is called\n   235→**Then** it produces the same URLs as the current `status.ts` implementation\n   236→\n   237→### Story 12-4: Shared test utilities and fixtures\n   238→\n   239→As a developer,\n   240→I want reusable test helpers and fixtures,\n   241→So that tests don't duplicate mock setup across 50+ files.\n   242→\n   243→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   244→\n   245→**Given** `src/lib/__tests__/fixtures/` exists\n   246→**When** inspected\n   247→**Then** it contains: `cargo-toml-variants.ts`, `state-builders.ts`, `mock-factories.ts`\n   248→\n   249→**Given** `src/lib/__tests__/helpers.ts` exists\n   250→**When** test files import from it\n   251→**Then** common patterns (mock Docker, mock fs, create temp state) are one-liners\n   252→\n   253→---\n   254→\n   255→## Epic 13: Agent Abstraction\n   256→\n   257→Ralph behind an AgentDriver interface.\n   258→\n   259→### Story 13-1: Create AgentDriver interface and types\n   260→\n   261→As a developer,\n   262→I want an `AgentDriver` interface that abstracts agent execution,\n   263→So that Ralph can be replaced or supplemented without touching 28 files.\n   264→\n   265→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   266→\n   267→**Given** `src/lib/agents/types.ts` exists\n   268→**When** inspected\n   269→**Then** it defines `AgentDriver`, `AgentProcess`, `AgentEvent` types\n   270→\n   271→**Given** the `AgentEvent` type\n   272→**When** inspected\n   273→**Then** it covers: `tool-start`, `tool-complete`, `text`, `story-complete`, `story-failed`, `iteration`, `retry`, `result`\n   274→\n   275→### Story 13-2: Implement RalphDriver\n   276→\n   277→As a developer,\n   278→I want Ralph wrapped in an `AgentDriver` implementation,\n   279→So that ralph-specific behavior is isolated in one file.\n   280→\n   281→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   282→\n   283→**Given** `src/lib/agents/ralph.ts` exists\n   284→**When** inspected\n   285→**Then** it implements `AgentDriver` with: `spawn()` (builds ralph.sh args), `parseOutput()` (parses ralph stderr + stream-json)\n   286→\n   287→**Given** `run-helpers.ts` ralph-specific functions (`parseRalphMessage`, `parseIterationMessage`, `buildSpawnArgs`)\n   288→**When** migration completes\n   289→**Then** they're moved into `ralph.ts` and `run-helpers.ts` is deleted\n   290→\n   291→### Story 13-3: Migrate run.ts to use AgentDriver\n   292→\n   293→As a developer,\n   294→I want `run.ts` to use `AgentDriver` instead of directly spawning Ralph,\n   295→So that the run command is agent-agnostic.\n   296→\n   297→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   298→\n   299→**Given** `src/commands/run.ts`\n   300→**When** inspected\n   301→**Then** it imports `AgentDriver` and calls `driver.spawn()`, not `spawn('bash', [ralphPath, ...])`\n   302→\n   303→**Given** `resolveRalphPath()` in run.ts\n   304→**When** migration completes\n   305→**Then** it's moved into `ralph.ts` and run.ts uses `driver.getExecutablePath()`\n   306→\n   307→---\n   308→\n   309→## Epic 14: Process & Infrastructure Fixes\n   310→\n   311→Retro pipeline, tech debt gate, Docker fixes, observability choice, verify provisioning.\n   312→\n   313→### Story 14-1: Retro-to-sprint pipeline (Step 8b) + persistent epic-TD\n   314→\n   315→As a developer running harness-run,\n   316→I want retro action items to auto-create stories under epic-TD,\n   317→So that tech debt gets tracked and prioritized automatically.\n   318→\n   319→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   320→\n   321→**Given** a retro file with `### Fix Now` items\n   322→**When** Step 8b runs\n   323→**Then** new `TD-N-slug: backlog` entries appear in sprint-state.json under epic-TD\n   324→\n   325→**Given** `epic-TD` doesn't exist\n   326→**When** Step 8b creates the first TD story\n   327→**Then** `epic-TD` is created with `status: in-progress` (never transitions to `done`)\n   328→\n   329→**Given** a duplicate action item (80%+ word overlap with existing TD story)\n   330→**When** Step 8b processes it\n   331→**Then** it's skipped with `[INFO]` message\n   332→\n   333→### Story 14-2: Tech debt gate in story selection\n   334→\n   335→As a developer,\n   336→I want TD stories prioritized before new feature work,\n   337→So that debt gets paid before it accumulates further.\n   338→\n   339→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   340→\n   341→**Given** `epic-TD` has 3 backlog stories and a feature epic has 5 backlog stories\n   342→**When** harness-run Step 2 selects next story\n   343→**Then** TD stories are selected first\n   344→\n   345→**Given** all TD stories are `done`\n   346→**When** Step 2 selects next story\n   347→**Then** feature epic stories are selected normally\n   348→\n   349→### Story 14-3: Docker pre-check and orphan cleanup\n   350→\n   351→As a developer,\n   352→I want Docker availability checked BEFORE any verification attempt,\n   353→So that sessions don't burn 30 minutes on Docker failures.\n   354→\n   355→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   356→\n   357→**Given** Docker daemon is not running\n   358→**When** harness-run Step 1 pre-flight runs\n   359→**Then** it fails fast with `[FAIL] Docker not available` without attempting any verification\n   360→\n   361→**Given** a leftover `codeharness-verify` container from a crashed session\n   362→**When** Step 1 pre-flight runs\n   363→**Then** the orphaned container is removed\n   364→\n   365→### Story 14-4: Observability backend choice (Victoria vs ELK vs Remote)\n   366→\n   367→As a developer initializing codeharness,\n   368→I want to choose my observability backend and provide remote endpoints,\n   369→So that I'm not locked into VictoriaMetrics with hardcoded ports.\n   370→\n   371→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   372→\n   373→**Given** `codeharness init --observability-backend elk`\n   374→**When** init runs\n   375→**Then** state stores `otlp.backend: 'elk'` and ELK compose is used\n   376→\n   377→**Given** `codeharness init --otel-endpoint https://remote:4318 --logs-url https://remote:9200`\n   378→**When** init runs\n   379→**Then** no local Docker stack is started and state stores remote endpoints\n   380→\n   381→**Given** `otlp.backend` is `'elk'`\n   382→**When** `codeharness status --check-docker` runs\n   383→**Then** it checks ELK containers (not Victoria)\n   384→\n   385→### Story 14-5: Stack-aware verification Dockerfile generation\n   386→\n   387→As a developer verifying a Rust/Bevy project,\n   388→I want the verification Dockerfile generated with the correct toolchain and system libs,\n   389→So that verification doesn't waste time fixing container issues manually.\n   390→\n   391→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   392→\n   393→**Given** a Rust project with `bevy` in Cargo.toml\n   394→**When** `verify-env build` runs\n   395→**Then** the generated Dockerfile includes: correct Rust version, Bevy system libs (wayland, udev, alsa, x11, xkbcommon, fontconfig), clippy, cargo-tarpaulin\n   396→\n   397→**Given** `ENV PATH=\"/root/.cargo/bin:$PATH\"` in the generated Dockerfile\n   398→**When** `cargo tarpaulin` is run inside the container\n   399→**Then** it works without manual `source \"$HOME/.cargo/env\"`\n   400→\n   401→### Story 14-6: Subagent status ownership + time budget awareness\n   402→\n   403→As a developer running harness-run,\n   404→I want the orchestrator to own all status writes and respect time budgets,\n   405→So that status is always correct and sessions don't fail at verification.\n   406→\n   407→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   408→\n   409→**Given** a subagent completes dev-story but doesn't update sprint-state.json\n   410→**When** the orchestrator checks after subagent return\n   411→**Then** it updates the status itself\n   412→\n   413→**Given** 10 minutes remaining and next phase is verification (~20min)\n   414→**When** harness-run checks budget\n   415→**Then** it defers with `[INFO] deferring verify to next session`\n   416→\n   417→### Story 14-7: Fix beads sync, session flags, ralph story tracking, proof docs\n   418→\n   419→As a developer,\n   420→I want chronic infrastructure bugs fixed,\n   421→So that sessions stop wasting time on known issues.\n   422→\n   423→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   424→\n   425→**Given** a story file with `## Status: backlog` header\n   426→**When** `readStoryFileStatus()` runs\n   427→**Then** it returns `'backlog'` (handles `##` prefix)\n   428→\n   429→**Given** `bd` CLI is not installed\n   430→**When** `codeharness sync` runs\n   431→**Then** it prints `[INFO] beads CLI not installed — skipping` (not `[FAIL]`)\n   432→\n   433→**Given** `cargo test` passes\n   434→**When** `codeharness.local.md` is checked\n   435→**Then** `session_flags.tests_passed` is `true`\n   436→\n   437→**Given** ralph times out during a story\n   438→**When** timeout report is generated\n   439→**Then** `status.json` contains the correct `story` field (not `unknown`)\n   440→\n   441→**Given** the codeharness proof format\n   442→**When** `commands/harness-verify.md` is read\n   443→**Then** the expected markdown structure is documented\n   444→\n   445→---\n   446→\n   447→## Epic 15: Enforcement\n   448→\n   449→CI gates, ESLint rules, boundary tests, template migration.\n   450→\n   451→### Story 15-1: CI file size gate + fix remaining violations\n   452→\n   453→As a developer,\n   454→I want a CI check that fails if any `.ts` file exceeds 300 lines,\n   455→So that file size debt stops accumulating.\n   456→\n   457→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   458→\n   459→**Given** CI pipeline runs\n   460→**When** any `.ts` file in `src/` (excluding `__tests__/`) exceeds 300 lines\n   461→**Then** the build fails with the filename and line count\n   462→\n   463→**Given** all file splits from Epic 12 are complete\n   464→**When** CI gate is enabled\n   465→**Then** it passes (zero violations)\n   466→\n   467→### Story 15-2: ESLint no-empty-catch + boundary tests\n   468→\n   469→As a developer,\n   470→I want automated enforcement of error handling and module boundaries,\n   471→So that architectural rules aren't just documented but enforced.\n   472→\n   473→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   474→\n   475→**Given** ESLint runs\n   476→**When** a catch block is empty (no `// IGNORE:` comment)\n   477→**Then** it reports an error\n   478→\n   479→**Given** a boundary test scans `src/`\n   480→**When** it finds `stack === 'nodejs'` outside `src/lib/stacks/`\n   481→**Then** the test fails\n   482→\n   483→**Given** a boundary test scans module imports\n   484→**When** a module imports from another module's internal file (not index.ts)\n   485→**Then** the test fails\n   486→\n   487→### Story 15-3: Template migration — all templates to static files\n   488→\n   489→As a developer,\n   490→I want all templates in `templates/` as static files (not generated in TypeScript),\n   491→So that there's one template system.\n   492→\n   493→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   494→\n   495→**Given** `templates/dockerfiles/`, `templates/prompts/`, `templates/docs/` directories\n   496→**When** inspected\n   497→**Then** they contain all Dockerfile templates, prompt templates, and doc templates that were previously in `src/templates/*.ts`\n   498→\n   499→**Given** `src/templates/` TypeScript generators\n   500→**When** migration completes\n   501→**Then** they're replaced with `renderTemplate()` calls reading from `templates/`\n   502→\n   503→**Given** `renderTemplate('templates/dockerfiles/Dockerfile.nodejs', { TARBALL: 'package.tgz' })`\n   504→**When** called\n   505→**Then** it returns the same Dockerfile content as the current `nodejsTemplate()` function\n   506→\n   507→### Story 15-4: Fix ~40 TS compilation errors in test files\n   508→\n   509→As a developer,\n   510→I want `npx tsc --noEmit` to produce zero errors,\n   511→So that type safety is enforced across the entire codebase.\n   512→\n   513→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   514→\n   515→**Given** `npx tsc --noEmit` is run\n   516→**When** it completes\n   517→**Then** zero compilation errors (down from ~40)\n   518→\n   519→**Given** the fixes\n   520→**When** inspected\n   521→**Then** they're type annotation changes only — no logic changes\n   522→\n   523→### Story 15-5: Lint rule for bare exception swallowing\n   524→\n   525→As a developer,\n   526→I want code review to flag `except Exception: pass` (Python) and empty catch blocks,\n   527→So that error swallowing doesn't cause silent production incidents.\n   528→\n   529→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   530→\n   531→**Given** code-review subagent reviews Python code\n   532→**When** it finds `except Exception: pass`\n   533→**Then** it flags it as HIGH severity\n   534→\n   535→**Given** `post-write-check.sh` hook runs after writing a Python file\n   536→**When** the file contains `except Exception: pass`\n   537→**Then** it prints a warning\n   538→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01LQDoB3frbVL8WR6YH4vVCs","session_id":"e39a20db-e648-4f8f-85ec-e4fa22cf8d05","uuid":"0f49a08a-5320-4c09-a7e4-7b4785a84f1d","timestamp":"2026-03-24T08:20:54.337Z"}
