{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LQDoB3frbVL8WR6YH4vVCs","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/10-3-python-provider.md`.\n\n**Summary:**\n- Expanded the existing skeleton story into a full implementation story with 21 acceptance criteria (all tagged `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->`) and 19 tasks\n- Followed the exact pattern from story 10-2 (NodejsProvider)\n- Traced every Python-specific branch in the codebase: `coverage.ts`, `otlp.ts`, `stack-detect.ts`, `dockerfile-template.ts`, `docs-scaffold.ts`\n- Included shared utility extraction (`hasPythonDep`, `getPythonDepsContent` into `utils.ts`)\n- Did not modify `sprint-status.yaml`, did not `git add` or `git commit`\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Problems encountered:**\n- None.\n\n**Workarounds applied:**\n- The epic definition mentions \"CLI entry points\" and \"library patterns\" for Python app type detection, but the actual codebase (`stack-detect.ts`) does not have CLI or library detection for Python — only agent, web, server (via entry-point files), and generic fallback. The ACs and tasks reflect the actual code, not the aspirational epic text.\n\n**Risks identified:**\n- All ACs are tagged `cli-verifiable`, which is accurate — they are all unit-testable with `npm test`. No integration-required ACs exist because this story only creates the provider class and tests; it does not modify consumers (deferred to 10-5).\n- The `getProjectName()` method for Python is new logic (not extracted from an existing consumer). The epic mentions \"Read from `pyproject.toml` `[project] name`\" but there is no existing implementation to extract. The task specifies a TOML regex approach, which is fragile for edge cases (inline comments, multi-line values). A proper TOML parser would be better but adds a dependency.\n- The `hasPythonDep()` regex from `stack-detect.ts` is somewhat fragile for packages with hyphens/underscores (Python normalizes these). The existing implementation is carried forward as-is.\n\n**Observations:**\n- The `PYTHON_OTLP_PACKAGES` in the existing code are `['opentelemetry-distro', 'opentelemetry-exporter-otlp']`, not `['opentelemetry-sdk', 'opentelemetry-instrumentation']` as stated in the original story skeleton's technical notes. The ACs use the actual values from `otlp.ts`.\n- Python has no `patchStartScript()` — OTLP uses the `opentelemetry-instrument` wrapper command via env vars, unlike Node.js which patches `--require` into `package.json` scripts."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: aadd2ce30fdff7e78 (use SendMessage with to: 'aadd2ce30fdff7e78' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 52538\ntool_uses: 35\nduration_ms: 146000</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e39a20db-e648-4f8f-85ec-e4fa22cf8d05","uuid":"8150b4ce-b15d-4660-8ba5-bfeefaa79129","timestamp":"2026-03-24T08:23:07.049Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /create-story for story 10-3-python-provider. The sprint-status.yaml is at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/sprint-status.yaml. Auto-discover the next backlog story and create it. For each AC, append `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->` or `<!-- verification: integration-required -->` based on whether the AC can be verified by running CLI commands in a subprocess. ACs referencing workflows, sprint planning, user sessions, or external system interactions should be tagged as integration-required. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Problems encountered (errors, ambiguities in epic definition, missing context)\n- Workarounds applied (anything you did that felt hacky or suboptimal)\n- Risks identified (ACs that seem untestable, unclear requirements, missing dependencies)\n- Observations (anything surprising or noteworthy about this story)\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`","agentId":"aadd2ce30fdff7e78","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/10-3-python-provider.md`.\n\n**Summary:**\n- Expanded the existing skeleton story into a full implementation story with 21 acceptance criteria (all tagged `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->`) and 19 tasks\n- Followed the exact pattern from story 10-2 (NodejsProvider)\n- Traced every Python-specific branch in the codebase: `coverage.ts`, `otlp.ts`, `stack-detect.ts`, `dockerfile-template.ts`, `docs-scaffold.ts`\n- Included shared utility extraction (`hasPythonDep`, `getPythonDepsContent` into `utils.ts`)\n- Did not modify `sprint-status.yaml`, did not `git add` or `git commit`\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Problems encountered:**\n- None.\n\n**Workarounds applied:**\n- The epic definition mentions \"CLI entry points\" and \"library patterns\" for Python app type detection, but the actual codebase (`stack-detect.ts`) does not have CLI or library detection for Python — only agent, web, server (via entry-point files), and generic fallback. The ACs and tasks reflect the actual code, not the aspirational epic text.\n\n**Risks identified:**\n- All ACs are tagged `cli-verifiable`, which is accurate — they are all unit-testable with `npm test`. No integration-required ACs exist because this story only creates the provider class and tests; it does not modify consumers (deferred to 10-5).\n- The `getProjectName()` method for Python is new logic (not extracted from an existing consumer). The epic mentions \"Read from `pyproject.toml` `[project] name`\" but there is no existing implementation to extract. The task specifies a TOML regex approach, which is fragile for edge cases (inline comments, multi-line values). A proper TOML parser would be better but adds a dependency.\n- The `hasPythonDep()` regex from `stack-detect.ts` is somewhat fragile for packages with hyphens/underscores (Python normalizes these). The existing implementation is carried forward as-is.\n\n**Observations:**\n- The `PYTHON_OTLP_PACKAGES` in the existing code are `['opentelemetry-distro', 'opentelemetry-exporter-otlp']`, not `['opentelemetry-sdk', 'opentelemetry-instrumentation']` as stated in the original story skeleton's technical notes. The ACs use the actual values from `otlp.ts`.\n- Python has no `patchStartScript()` — OTLP uses the `opentelemetry-instrument` wrapper command via env vars, unlike Node.js which patches `--require` into `package.json` scripts."}],"totalDurationMs":146000,"totalTokens":52538,"totalToolUseCount":35,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4664,"cache_read_input_tokens":47210,"output_tokens":663,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4664},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
