{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01YZ12WoiG8irLuRWkEzwTMs","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Session Retrospective — 2026-03-24\n     2→\n     3→**Sprint:** Operational Excellence (Architecture v3 Migration phase)\n     4→**Session:** 8 (continuation from session 7 on 2026-03-23)\n     5→**Session start:** ~07:39 UTC\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## 1. Session Summary\n    10→\n    11→| Story | Epic | Outcome | Pipeline Stages |\n    12→|-------|------|---------|-----------------|\n    13→| 9-2-state-schema-migration-multi-stack | Epic 9 (Multi-Stack) | done (carryover from session 7) | create-story, dev-story, code-review all completed |\n    14→| 10-1-stackprovider-interface-and-registry | Epic 10 (Stack Provider Pattern) | done — status: verifying | create-story, dev-story, code-review all completed |\n    15→\n    16→Both stories completed all pipeline stages (story creation, development, code review with fixes). Story 9-2 was carried over from session 7 (2026-03-23) where it went through create-story and dev-story; code review happened at the boundary. Story 10-1 was fully executed in this session.\n    17→\n    18→**Net progress:** Epic 9 fully closed (all 5 stories done). Epic 10 started — 1 of 5 stories done, 4 remain in backlog.\n    19→\n    20→---\n    21→\n    22→## 2. Issues Analysis\n    23→\n    24→### Bugs Discovered During Implementation or Verification\n    25→\n    26→| Severity | Story | Issue | Fixed? |\n    27→|----------|-------|-------|--------|\n    28→| HIGH | 9-2 | `init-project.ts` never persisted multi-stacks to state file — `detectStacks()` results lost on init | Yes |\n    29→| HIGH | 10-1 | `src/lib/stacks/index.ts` barrel file at 0% coverage — auto-registration never tested | Yes |\n    30→| HIGH | 10-1 | `src/lib/stacks/nodejs.ts` at 17.64% coverage — 13 stub methods uncalled | Yes |\n    31→| MEDIUM | 9-2 | `writeState()` mutated caller's state object via `state.stack = state.stacks[0]` side effect | Yes |\n    32→| MEDIUM | 9-2 | `isValidState()` accepted `stacks: [42, true]` — no element type checking | Yes |\n    33→| MEDIUM | 9-2 | `recoverCorruptedState()` produced inconsistent `stack: null` / `stacks: ['nodejs']` | Yes |\n    34→| MEDIUM | 10-1 | Bare `catch {}` in registry.ts line 73 — readdirSync errors silently swallowed | Yes |\n    35→\n    36→Code review caught 7 HIGH/MEDIUM bugs across both stories. All were fixed in-session. The `init-project.ts` persistence bug (9-2) was the most impactful — multi-stack detection would have been silently broken at runtime.\n    37→\n    38→### Workarounds Applied (Tech Debt Introduced)\n    39→\n    40→1. **`stacks: ['nodejs'] as StackName[]`** in `stack.test.ts` — readonly tuple workaround. Minor, localized to tests.\n    41→2. **`migrateState()` casts `raw.stack as StackName`** without validating against known stack names (9-2, LOW, not fixed). Invalid stack names in old state files would pass migration unchecked.\n    42→3. **`recoverCorruptedState()` calls both `detectStack()` and `detectStacks()`** — double detection (9-2, LOW, not fixed). Performance waste, not a correctness issue.\n    43→\n    44→### Code Quality Concerns\n    45→\n    46→1. **`StackDetection` type duplicated** between `registry.ts` and `stack-detect.ts` (10-1, MEDIUM, deferred to story 10-5). Expected — the old and new codepaths coexist until consumer migration.\n    47→2. **`_resetRegistry` test-only utility leaking into public barrel export** (10-1, LOW, not fixed). Should be conditionally exported or moved to test helpers.\n    48→3. **Parallel detection codepaths** — `stack-detect.ts` retains hardcoded detection while `registry.ts` has marker-based detection. Two ways to detect stacks coexist until story 10-5.\n    49→4. **~10 pre-existing TS compilation errors** in test files (bridge, run, stack, status, teardown, deps, sync). Not from this session but noted by dev agents.\n    50→\n    51→### Verification Gaps\n    52→\n    53→- **`recoverCorruptedState()` recovery path for `stacks` field** not directly unit-tested — would need planted `package.json` in temp dir (9-2).\n    54→- **`init-project.test.ts` has zero assertions on `stacks` field** after init. No test for recovery when root null but subdirs have stacks (9-2).\n    55→- Both stories currently in `verifying` status — final verification pass not yet completed.\n    56→\n    57→### Tooling/Infrastructure Problems\n    58→\n    59→- No sandbox, permission, or CLI issues reported this session.\n    60→- Pre-existing TS compilation errors (~10 test files) continue to be noise but do not block execution.\n    61→\n    62→---\n    63→\n    64→## 3. What Went Well\n    65→\n    66→- **Code review pipeline is catching real bugs.** 7 HIGH/MEDIUM issues found and fixed before merge. The `init-project.ts` persistence bug would have been a production defect.\n    67→- **Epic 9 fully completed.** All 5 multi-stack stories done across sessions 6-8. Multi-stack detection, state migration, init orchestration, Dockerfile generation, and consumer migration all landed.\n    68→- **Story 10-1 clean execution.** StackProvider interface + registry created with 30 new tests, 97.06% coverage, backward compatibility confirmed (79 existing stack-detect tests still pass).\n    69→- **Backward compatibility maintained.** `stack-detect.ts` re-exports from new `stacks/types.ts` — existing imports unbroken.\n    70→- **Test suite healthy.** 3098+ tests passing, 0 failures, all 127 files above 80% coverage floor.\n    71→\n    72→---\n    73→\n    74→## 4. What Went Wrong\n    75→\n    76→- **Two LOW-severity issues intentionally not fixed in 9-2.** The `migrateState()` unchecked cast and double-detection in recovery are accepted tech debt. Neither is likely to cause production issues but both reduce code quality.\n    77→- **Coverage gaps in init-project tests for stacks field.** Code review flagged this but it was not addressed — the `stacks` field integration in init is tested implicitly but not explicitly.\n    78→- **Pre-existing TS errors are accumulating.** ~10 test files have unrelated compilation issues. These create noise in every dev session and risk masking new errors. Story 15-4 exists for this but remains in backlog.\n    79→- **Only 1 new story completed this session.** Session 7 carryover (9-2 review) consumed time. Throughput was effectively 1 story in session 8.\n    80→\n    81→---\n    82→\n    83→## 5. Lessons Learned\n    84→\n    85→### Repeat\n    86→- **Code review as a mandatory pipeline stage.** It caught the `init-project.ts` persistence bug and the `isValidState()` type-checking gap — both would have been shipped otherwise.\n    87→- **Stub-first provider pattern.** Creating NodejsProvider as a stub in 10-1 (with `throw 'not yet implemented'`) keeps the story focused and the next stories (10-2 through 10-4) well-scoped.\n    88→- **Backward compatibility through re-exports.** The `stack-detect.ts` re-export pattern avoids a big-bang migration.\n    89→\n    90→### Avoid\n    91→- **Leaving coverage gaps flagged by review unfixed.** The init-project stacks assertion gap was called out but not addressed. Future sessions should fix all review findings or explicitly defer with a tracked issue.\n    92→- **Allowing test-only utilities in public exports.** `_resetRegistry` should never have been in the barrel file. Establish a convention (separate `testing.ts` export or conditional export).\n    93→\n    94→---\n    95→\n    96→## 6. Action Items\n    97→\n    98→### Fix Now (Before Next Session)\n    99→- None critical. Both stories are functionally complete with all HIGH/MEDIUM issues resolved.\n   100→\n   101→### Fix Soon (Next Sprint / Next Session)\n   102→1. **Complete stories 10-2, 10-3, 10-4** — Full NodejsProvider, PythonProvider, RustProvider implementations. These are the immediate next work items.\n   103→2. **Add explicit `stacks` field assertions to `init-project.test.ts`** — Coverage gap flagged in 9-2 review.\n   104→3. **Move `_resetRegistry` out of public barrel export** — Either `stacks/testing.ts` or conditional export.\n   105→4. **Validate stack names in `migrateState()`** — Check `raw.stack` against known `StackName` values before casting.\n   106→\n   107→### Backlog (Track But Not Urgent)\n   108→1. **Story 15-4: Fix pre-existing TS compilation errors** — 10 test files with unrelated errors. Growing noise.\n   109→2. **Story 15-2/15-5: Lint rules for bare catch and exception swallowing** — The `catch {}` in registry.ts was caught manually; a lint rule would catch these automatically.\n   110→3. **Deduplicate `StackDetection` type** — Blocked until story 10-5 migrates all consumers to the new registry.\n   111→4. **Eliminate double detection in `recoverCorruptedState()`** — Call `detectStacks()` once and derive `detectStack()` from it.\n   112→5. **Add `recoverCorruptedState()` integration test with planted `package.json`** — Currently no direct test for stacks field recovery.\n   113→\n   114→---\n   115→\n   116→# Session Retrospective — 2026-03-24 (Session 9)\n   117→\n   118→**Sprint:** Operational Excellence (Architecture v3 Migration phase)\n   119→**Session:** 9 (autonomous ralph run, continuation from session 8)\n   120→**Session start:** ~07:54 UTC\n   121→**Appended:** 2026-03-24\n   122→\n   123→---\n   124→\n   125→## 1. Session Summary\n   126→\n   127→| Story | Epic | Outcome | Pipeline Stages |\n   128→|-------|------|---------|-----------------|\n   129→| 10-2-nodejs-provider | Epic 10 (Stack Provider Pattern) | verifying | create-story, dev-story, code-review all completed |\n   130→\n   131→Story 10-2 was the sole story attempted this session. Ralph picked it as the next Tier D backlog item after 10-1 completed in session 8. The story went through all three pipeline stages: story creation (rewrote the minimal 3-AC spec into a detailed 18-AC version), development (full NodejsProvider implementation), and code review (4 issues found, all HIGH/MEDIUM fixed). Status is `verifying` — awaiting final verification pass.\n   132→\n   133→**Net progress:** Epic 10 now has 2 of 5 stories done (10-1, 10-2). Stories 10-3 (Python), 10-4 (Rust), and 10-5 (consumer migration) remain in backlog.\n   134→\n   135→---\n   136→\n   137→## 2. Issues Analysis\n   138→\n   139→### Bugs Discovered During Implementation or Verification\n   140→\n   141→| Severity | Story | Issue | Fixed? |\n   142→|----------|-------|-------|--------|\n   143→| HIGH | 10-2 | `parseTestOutput()` vitest regex didn't capture skipped count — total calculation was wrong | Yes |\n   144→| HIGH | 10-2 | `parseTestOutput()` jest regex failed when `skipped` appeared between `passed` and `total` — rewrote to extract fields independently | Yes |\n   145→| MEDIUM | 10-2 | `utils.ts` at 70.58% coverage (below 80% floor) — `readTextSafe()` had no tests. Added `utils.test.ts` with 9 tests | Yes |\n   146→| MEDIUM | 10-2 | `nodejs.ts` catch branch in `patchStartScript` for malformed JSON was untested. Added test | Yes |\n   147→\n   148→Code review caught 4 issues (2 HIGH, 2 MEDIUM). All fixed in-session. The `parseTestOutput()` bugs were real correctness issues — test result parsing would have reported wrong totals for vitest projects and certain jest output formats.\n   149→\n   150→### Workarounds Applied (Tech Debt Introduced)\n   151→\n   152→1. **`CoverageToolInfo` type mismatch left unresolved.** `stacks/types.ts` defines `{ tool, configFile? }` but `coverage.ts` uses `{ tool, runCommand, reportFormat }`. Provider uses the stacks/types version. Reconciliation explicitly deferred to story 10-5.\n   153→2. **`OtlpResult` type mismatch left unresolved.** `stacks/types.ts` defines `{ success, packagesInstalled, error? }` but `otlp.ts` uses `{ status, packages_installed, start_script_patched, env_vars_configured, error? }`. Same deferral to 10-5.\n   154→3. **Consumer branches not removed.** Epic AC3 calls for removing all Node.js if/else branches from consumers, but the incremental migration strategy defers this to 10-5. AC18 (zero regressions) was substituted to match the actual incremental intent.\n   155→\n   156→### Code Quality Concerns\n   157→\n   158→1. **Two parallel type systems for the same concepts.** `CoverageToolInfo` and `OtlpResult` have incompatible shapes in the old (`coverage.ts`, `otlp.ts`) and new (`stacks/types.ts`) codepaths. This will cause confusion until 10-5 reconciles them.\n   159→2. **`patchStartScript` is optional on the interface but implemented in NodejsProvider.** Consumers need `provider.patchStartScript?.(dir)` optional chaining. Easy to forget.\n   160→3. **Pre-existing TS errors grew from ~10 to ~50** across test files (bridge, run, deps, etc.). The dev agent reported 50 type errors unrelated to this story. This is significantly worse than session 8's ~10 and suggests either new errors were introduced by other changes or the count was underreported previously.\n   161→\n   162→### Verification Gaps\n   163→\n   164→- **LOW (not fixed):** `readTextSafe` catch branch at 93.33% — race condition between `existsSync`/`readFileSync`, not worth mocking.\n   165→- **LOW (not fixed):** `registry.ts` at 94.73% — uncovered lines from story 10-1, not in scope for 10-2.\n   166→- Story status is `verifying` — final verification pass not yet completed.\n   167→\n   168→### Tooling/Infrastructure Problems\n   169→\n   170→- No sandbox, permission, or CLI issues reported.\n   171→- Story creation agent overwrote the existing minimal `10-2-nodejs-provider.md` without issue. The overwrite was intentional and produced a better spec.\n   172→\n   173→---\n   174→\n   175→## 3. What Went Well\n   176→\n   177→- **Full pipeline completion for 10-2.** Story creation, development, and code review all ran to completion in a single autonomous ralph session.\n   178→- **Code review continues to catch real bugs.** The two `parseTestOutput()` regex bugs were correctness issues that would have shipped without review. The pattern of review catching HIGH-severity bugs is consistent across sessions 8 and 9.\n   179→- **Coverage discipline held.** When `utils.ts` dropped below the 80% floor, the reviewer flagged it and 9 new tests were added. Final coverage: 97.09% overall, all 128 files above floor.\n   180→- **Test suite grew healthily.** 3267 tests total, up from 3098 in session 8 (169 new tests). 64/64 nodejs-specific tests pass. Zero regressions across the full suite.\n   181→- **Story spec quality improved.** Rewriting the minimal 3-AC story into an 18-AC version with task breakdown and verification tags gave the dev agent much better guidance.\n   182→\n   183→---\n   184→\n   185→## 4. What Went Wrong\n   186→\n   187→- **Type system divergence is growing.** Two type mismatches (`CoverageToolInfo`, `OtlpResult`) are now tracked tech debt. Both are deferred to 10-5, but 10-5 is accumulating scope — it needs to reconcile types AND migrate all consumers AND remove old branches. Risk of 10-5 becoming too large.\n   188→- **Pre-existing TS errors reportedly jumped from ~10 to ~50.** Whether this is a real increase or just better counting is unclear, but 50 type errors in test files is significant noise. Story 15-4 remains in backlog with no scheduled date.\n   189→- **Only 1 story completed per session (again).** Session 8 did 1 new story; session 9 did 1 story. The pipeline (create + dev + review) for a medium-complexity story consumes an entire ralph session. This is the expected throughput but it means Epic 10 will take 3 more sessions minimum.\n   190→- **Epic AC3 had to be softened.** The original AC required removing all consumer branches, but incremental migration made that impractical for this story. The AC substitution was reasonable but represents scope drift from the epic's original intent.\n   191→\n   192→---\n   193→\n   194→## 5. Lessons Learned\n   195→\n   196→### Repeat\n   197→- **Rewriting minimal story specs before development.** The 3-AC to 18-AC rewrite for 10-2 produced better outcomes. Dev agents work better with detailed ACs and task breakdowns.\n   198→- **Independent field extraction in regex parsers.** The rewritten `parseTestOutput()` extracts `passed`, `failed`, `skipped`, `total` independently rather than trying to match one monolithic pattern. More robust against format variations.\n   199→- **Adding tests when coverage drops below floor.** Catching `utils.ts` at 70.58% and adding 9 tests is the right discipline. Do not let coverage debt accumulate.\n   200→\n   201→### Avoid\n   202→- **Deferring too much scope to a single future story.** Story 10-5 now owns: type reconciliation (CoverageToolInfo, OtlpResult), consumer migration, branch removal, and StackDetection deduplication. Consider splitting 10-5 into sub-stories before it starts.\n   203→- **Ignoring growing TS error counts.** 50 pre-existing type errors is no longer \"noise\" — it's a quality signal. Prioritize 15-4 or at least triage which errors are new vs. old.\n   204→\n   205→---\n   206→\n   207→## 6. Action Items\n   208→\n   209→### Fix Now (Before Next Session)\n   210→- None critical. All HIGH/MEDIUM issues from 10-2 review are resolved. Story is functionally complete pending verification.\n   211→\n   212→### Fix Soon (Next Sprint / Next Session)\n   213→1. **Complete story 10-3 (PythonProvider)** — Next in Epic 10 sequence.\n   214→2. **Triage pre-existing TS errors.** Determine whether the jump from ~10 to ~50 is real or a counting difference. If real, escalate story 15-4 priority.\n   215→3. **Consider splitting story 10-5.** It has at least 4 distinct responsibilities. Break into: (a) type reconciliation, (b) consumer migration, (c) branch cleanup, (d) deduplication cleanup.\n   216→4. **Verify story 10-2.** Run final verification pass to move from `verifying` to `done`.\n   217→\n   218→### Backlog (Track But Not Urgent)\n   219→1. **`readTextSafe` catch branch coverage** — 93.33%, race condition edge case. Not worth the mock complexity.\n   220→2. **`registry.ts` coverage gap at 94.73%** — Lines from story 10-1, will naturally improve as more providers register.\n   221→3. **`patchStartScript` optional chaining documentation** — Ensure consumer migration in 10-5 uses `?.` consistently.\n   222→4. All items from session 8 backlog remain open (15-4, 15-2/15-5, StackDetection dedup, double detection, recoverCorruptedState test).\n   223→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_018CgAWhHkypcyYCaCELLdSy","session_id":"e39a20db-e648-4f8f-85ec-e4fa22cf8d05","uuid":"6747177b-e50d-443e-95b6-fc8582d7c138","timestamp":"2026-03-24T08:35:15.824Z"}
